The Consultative Committee of Belgium on 19 July, 2021 has confirmed the proposals of the Interministerial Conference on Public Health and has invited the Ministers of Health to:
update and complete the summary of vaccination coverage;
strengthen consultation with professional groups to sensitize healthcare providers further;
give healthcare providers who have not yet been vaccinated another opportunity to get vaccinated;
take the necessary initiatives, in consultation with healthcare institutions and occupational health services, to achieve public reporting of vaccination coverage per institution as soon as possible.

Are you travelling from India, South Africa or Brazil? You are not allowed to travel to Belgium unless you have Belgian nationality, your main residence is in Belgium or for the following essential journeys:
Transport personnel, freight and cargo personnel and mariners travelling for work, provided that they have a certificate from the employer;
A trip undertaken by diplomats, staff of international organisations and people invited by international organisations whose physical presence is required for the proper functioning of those organisations when performing their duties, provided that they hold an essential travel certificate issued by the Belgian diplomatic mission or consular post.

On March 24, 2020, the Belgian Government announced a health resources policy to combat drug shortages. The policy can be renewed on a monthly basis for up to one year, ending no later than March 31, 2021. The law empowers the government to:
- restrict or prohibit the export of a drug or raw material;
- temporarily restrict the delivery of a drug, including magistral or official drugs;
- temporarily limit the supply of a drug or raw material to pharmacies to a quantity determined by the pharmacy;
- temporarily reserve the delivery of medicine, including magistral or official drugs, to hospital pharmacies;
- order the redistribution of the stock of a drug or raw material either by returning to the wholesaler or by a direct redistribution between pharmacies;
- requisition stocks of a drug or raw material for redistribution; 
- allow and regulate the delivery of medicines by doctors or other health care professionals.

September 23, 2020: With regard to testing, Belgium has made several decisions in line with its "Health Resources" policy, namely: 

To increase the testing capacity of existing triage centres and establishing new screening points. The federated entities are currently working on it;
A call-centre will be set up to group all questions in a single point of information and to reduce the burden on general practitioners;
To set up a platform to book appointments and dispatch requests to the available centres.
To lighten the administrative burden on doctors, a “Corona doctor’s note” will be created in mid-October for certain asymptomatic cases - such as people returning from their holidays, for example;
Or patients can be encouraged to consult their test results online, in particular via the Cozo system or masanté.be.

On 23rd September the Prime Minister announced that in Belgium with regard to testing, a series of decisions have been taken in this area:  
1) To increase the testing capacity of existing triage centres and establishing new screening points. The federated entities are currently working on it;  
2) A call-centre will be set up to group all questions in a single point of information and to reduce the burden on general practitioners;  
3) To set up a platform to book appointments and dispatch requests to the available centres.  
4) To lighten the administrative burden on doctors, a "Corona doctor's note" will be created in mid-October for certain asymptomatic cases - such as people returning from their holidays  
5) Patients can be encouraged to consult their test results online, in particular via the Cozo system.

Belgium, 20 May 2020. 
The Minister of Security and the Interior has announced measures to limit the spread of COVID-19.
The persons are required to stay at home or in a secondary residence which they either own, tenants for a period of at least one year, excluding mobile second homes which have not yet been installed on a fixed location. It is forbidden to be on the public roads and in public places, except when necessary.
In particular, the following are considered as necessary travel such as:
-go to the places whose opening is authorised on the basis of Articles 1, 2 and 3 and reverted thereto;
- have access bank ATMs and post offices;
- have access to medical care;
- meet family needs, such as visiting partners or children as part of co-parenting;
- provide assistance and care to the elderly,x minors, to persons with disabilities and vulnerable persons;
- take care of animals;
- make business trips, including commuting;
- travel as part of a volunteer activity within a company in a sector or an essential service referred to in Article 3, including commuting;
- carry out the activities referred to in Article 5, paragraph 2 and Article 5bis;
- make the trips in the context of Article 6;
- make trips as part of the sale and rental immovable property;

A household, little regardless of its size, is allowed to accommodate at home or within its second home up to four persons. These four people are always the same. They may or may not be part of the same household.

In order to allow the Brussels-Capital Region in Belgium to react to the pandemic COVID19, the Government may take all useful measures to prevent and treat urgently, under pain of serious danger, any situation which poses a problem within the strict framework of the pandemic COVID19 and its consequences from 19 march 2020, in particular in the following areas:
- the adaptation of the legal texts relating to the deadlines set by the legislation of the Brussels-Capital Region or adopted pursuant thereto;
- the adaptation of legal texts relating to areas impacted by the crisis and relating to regional matters;
- management of the socio-economic effects of the pandemic;
- measures related to prevention and safety on the regional territory;
- urgent health measures in relation to regional matters.
The decrees may repeal, complete, modify, or replace the ordinance provisions in force.

