Belgium, 1 November 2020.

Minister of the Interior of Belgium has announced on 1st November that companies and associations offering goods to consumers are closed to the public. But they may continue to operate through deliveries or an appointment system to collect goods ordered in advance in the open air, in compliance with rules to limit the spread of COVID-19. 

The following establishments or parts of the following establishments may remain open to the public in so far as they offer mainly essential goods, and only for the supply of of such goods:
(1) food stores, including night stores;
(2) hygiene and care stores;
(3) pet food stores ;
(4) pharmacies ;
(5) newsagents and bookstores ;
(6) petrol stations and fuel suppliers;
(7) telecommunications stores, excluding stores that only sell accessories;
(8) medical device stores;
(9) DIY stores;
(10) garden centres and nurseries;
(11) flower and plant shops;
(12) wholesale stores intended for professionals, but only for the benefit of the latter;
(13) specialized retail businesses that sell clothing fabrics;
(14) specialized retail businesses that sell knitting yarns and haberdashery;
(15) stationery stores.

